The Cinderteeth Mountains (Thrak-Essen) erupted after generations of ignored Khephari and Kethari seismic warnings.
The Ashfall Monsoon followed: three years of black volcanic rain over Kowloon's delta, the eastern desert, and the lowland caravan corridors.
Ash-laden water destroyed crops, contaminated wells with sulfur and calcium sediment, and made primary trade routes impassable.
The Salt Ledger Kingdoms collapsed as their road-taxation legitimacy dissolved with the roads themselves.
The village of Yen-Mak drowned in one night — six hundred dead — when a flash flood swallowed the delta settlement.
Yen-Mak's survivors crawling onto a basalt outcrop became the founding moment of Kowloon: enemy houses pulling the same ropes.
Displaced persons from ash-ruined settlements flooded Midgaard's intake systems, straining charter law.
Midgaard classified ashfall-displaced persons under emergency warrants; Ashborn were misclassified as a human subtype rather than a distinct people.
The Spirebound Conclave used the crisis to demand prisoner transfers from frontier cities in exchange for arcane defensive aid.
Kiess (later founded on Evermeet's ruins) wrote anti-sealed-warrant doctrine into its charter as a direct response to Ashfall-era governance.
Rakuen's founding as a southern relief city traces to Ashfall-era migration, when Midgaard's "resettled south" mechanism routed displaced populations southward.
The Cinderteeth's eruption cycle had been documented by Keeper survey crews; Ventspeaker guides had read it in vent gas patterns for generations.
The catastrophe is canonical evidence that institutional ignoring of non-human environmental testimony produces compounding disaster.

