Midgaard's emergency registry classified ashfall-displaced persons under the Ash-and-Iron intake warrant system.
The classification criteria used "unregistered person" and "debtor-adjacent" status to process populations arriving without ledger documentation.
Ashborn were entered in the registry under a human-subtype designation; no separate category existed and none was created during the emergency.
This misclassification determined labor assignment, resettlement routing, and access to emergency food allocation.
The Continuity faction holds that intake classification during crisis was a procedural necessity, not a policy statement.
The Reckoning faction holds that the misclassification was institutionally convenient: Ashborn labor capacity was high, and a human-subtype designation allowed their transfer under warrants applicable to human debtors.
Midgaard's trade ledgers retain financial records showing payment received for condemned-subject transfers to the Spirebound Conclave during the Ashfall years.
The ledger entries do not specify race; the intake warrants do.
Charter sovereignty arguments against opening the Ashfall-era warrants cite the risk of precedent for all sealed emergency orders.
The Temple of the Resounding Heart maintains memorial rolls from "the years the sun dimmed" — the most complete public record of Ashfall casualties held in Midgaard.

