Rakuen's founding population was substantially composed of Ashfall-era displaced persons routed south under Midgaard's "resettled south" welfare mechanism.
The resettlement routing was not chosen; it was assigned. Midgaard's intake system designated southern relief settlement as the destination for populations it could not absorb or did not want to register permanently.
Rakuen's founding myth of a "paradise city" built on cooperative burden-sharing was constructed partly over this less comfortable origin.
The Garden Ledger Clerks hold population records from the founding generation that include former Midgaard intake registry numbers alongside Rakuen registration numbers.
These dual-registry entries are the administrative record of Ashfall-era displacement: each one is a person who arrived with a Midgaard emergency classification and was assigned a Rakuen identity.
Rakuen's political class understands the Ashfall as the moment when the five-city burden distribution was set in a pattern that has not changed: Midgaard classifies, Rakuen absorbs.
The Ash Requiem memorial rite traces to this founding generation's grief over orchard loss and cistern poisoning in the Ashfall years.
The Ash Plea and subsequent annexation petitions are downstream consequences of an Ashfall-era distribution of costs that was never formally renegotiated.

