Mafdet's Ledger Houses processed significantly increased off-continent cargo diversion during the Ashfall years as overland routes collapsed.
When caravan roads became impassable, high-value freight shifted to maritime channels; Mafdet's harbor authority expanded to handle volume previously routed overland.
The Swift Court's emergency cargo adjudication protocols, developed during the Ashfall years, remain active law: any manifest disrupted by volcanic or seismic event qualifies for mercy-freight reclassification.
Mafdet's oaths and attestation requirements for ashfall-displaced cargo manifests created a new legal category: "origin-uncertain goods" from settlements that no longer existed as legal entities.
The attestation for origin-uncertain goods required a living witness oath rather than a registry document — a practical adaptation to the destruction of records in ash-flooded settlements.
Mafdet has no memorial for the Ashfall as such, but its maritime cargo law carries the Ashfall's institutional fingerprint in every mercy-freight clause.
The co-signature Mafdet provided for Rakuen's Iron Compact Appeal was understood locally as a Ashfall-legacy obligation: the cities that absorbed Ashfall costs deserve better than permanent external status.

