---
Ashborn were the people most directly made by the Ashfall and simultaneously the people most badly misclassified by Midgaard's response to it.
The intake warrant system had no category for a population whose physical transformation resulted from surviving the eruption.
"Human subtype" was the default when registry clerks encountered people who appeared human but carried visible volcanic mineral threading in skin and joints.
The designation mattered practically: human-subtype status made Ashborn subject to human-debtor warrants, which could authorize labor transfer to the Spirebound Conclave.
Ashborn oral tradition preserves accounts of individuals who arrived at Midgaard's intake yards, were registered under emergency warrants, and did not return.
The Conclave's Ember Canon doctrine — theorizing fire as the most fundamental transformative force — was partly inspired by Ashborn physiology; the Conclave attempted to replicate volcanic transformation deliberately and obtained experimental subjects partly through Midgaard's warrant system.
The Reckoning faction's demand to open Ashfall-era warrants is understood by Ashborn communities as a matter of identity documentation: the warrants contain the first institutional record of their people's existence, written by the institution that harmed them.
Midgaard's Continuity faction has not formally acknowledged the misclassification.

