---
Khephari communities in the Cinderteeth foothills had been reading volcanic vent-gas patterns for generations before the eruption.
Keeper survey records from the Age of Measures documented Khephari seismic assessment capacity as "anomalous sensory capacity for seismic assessment — mechanism unconfirmed but accuracy confirmed."
The confirmation was in writing. The warnings were not acted upon.
Midgaard's charter archives hold Keeper-era correspondence citing Khephari route-closure recommendations for Cinderteeth-adjacent passages; the recommendations were overridden by commercial transit interests.
After the eruption, Khephari earth-sense was credited in academic reconstruction but not in institutional reform: the post-Ashfall survey commissions that redesigned Cinderteeth routing did not include Khephari representatives.
Midgaard's registry classified some Khephari displaced by the eruption as "non-citizen corridor peoples" — the same legal category applied to them in Keeper-era survey law.
The Reckoning faction has proposed creating a formal "pre-institutional knowledge" category in charter law to give legal weight to non-registry warning systems.
The Continuity faction's counter-position is that charter law cannot adjudicate knowledge systems that predate the charter.

