---
Deltari communities had managed the delta's flood timing and sediment flow for generations before the Ashfall Monsoon.
Their multi-generational hydraulic knowledge — where water went in high flood, which channels drained first, which elevations survived — was the practical knowledge that kept more people alive during the black-rain years than any institutional response did.
The village of Yen-Mak, which drowned in one night, was Deltari-majority; its loss is recorded in Kowloon's Black Ledger founding entries.
Kowloon's drainage and terrace design incorporated Deltari flood-pattern knowledge explicitly: House Tahn-Rei (Ferry Masters) preserved the delta mud-maps in memory, and those maps became Kowloon's hydraulic infrastructure plans.
The Deltari communities' loss during the Ashfall was proportionally higher than other populations because delta settlements had no high ground and no institutional claim on inland refuge.
Black Ledger entries from the proto-Kowloon period include Deltari names in the condemned-debtor transfer lists — evidence that even among Ashfall victims, Deltari had least institutional protection.
Kowloon's ration code and central ledger system were designed partly to prevent a future scenario in which Deltari hydraulic labor was essential while Deltari civic standing was negligible.

